    body: "Ember Days (Quatuor Anni Tempora) are groups of three days—Wednesday, Friday, and Saturday—occurring near the beginning of each of the four seasons. Their origins may reach back to the Roman agricultural calendar, Christianized to sanctify the changing seasons with fasting, prayer, and almsgiving. Pope Gelasius I (d. 496) fixed them to their traditional weeks, and they became the customary times for conferring Holy Orders. Though made optional in the 1969 liturgical reform, many dioceses and traditional communities continue to observe them. The Saturday Ember Day Masses featured extended Old Testament readings reminiscent of ancient vigil liturgies.",
