    oneLiner: "Medieval textual and musical additions to the liturgy that eventually gave birth to Western dramatic tradition.",
    body: "Tropes were interpolations of new text and music into existing liturgical chants, flourishing from the ninth to the twelfth centuries, particularly in Benedictine monasteries like St. Gall and Winchester. The most famous trope, the Quem Quaeritis dialogue for Easter ('Whom do you seek in the tomb?'), evolved from a simple antiphonal exchange into a fully dramatized scene, generally considered the origin of medieval liturgical drama and, ultimately, of all Western theater. Other tropes expanded the Introit, Kyrie, and other Mass propers. The Council of Trent suppressed most tropes in favor of liturgical uniformity, though their influence persists in the sequences and in the dramatic character of Holy Week liturgies.",
