    category: "morality",
    tags: ["law", "prudence", "conscience", "aquinas"],
    oneLiner: "The virtue of interpreting a law according to the legislator's intention when strict literal application would produce an unjust or unreasonable result.",
    body: "Epikeia (from the Greek epieikeia, 'reasonableness') is a concept developed by Aristotle and adopted by St. Thomas Aquinas in the Summa Theologiae (II-II, q. 120). It recognizes that no human legislator can foresee every circumstance, so there will be cases where the letter of the law fails to capture its spirit. In such cases, a person of prudence may act contrary to the strict wording of the law while remaining faithful to its deeper intention. Epikeia is not a loophole for laxity but a form of higher fidelity to justice. It applies to human (ecclesiastical and civil) law but never to divine or natural law, which admits no exceptions.",
