    body: "In moral theology, scandal (from the Greek skandalon, 'stumbling block') does not mean mere shock or outrage but specifically refers to an action or omission that provides the occasion for another to sin. The Catechism (CCC 2284-2287) distinguishes direct scandal—deliberately inducing someone to sin—from indirect scandal, where one's bad example foreseeably leads others astray. Jesus warned gravely against scandal: 'Whoever causes one of these little ones to sin, it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck' (Matt 18:6). Those with authority, influence, or public visibility bear a proportionally greater responsibility to avoid scandal.",
