    body: "Rash judgment occurs when one assumes, without adequate foundation, that another person has committed a sin or acted from evil motives. The Catechism (CCC 2477) identifies it as a sin against the eighth commandment alongside detraction and calumny. St. Thomas Aquinas teaches that we are morally obligated to put the best interpretation on ambiguous actions of others (Summa Theologiae II-II, q. 60, a. 4). This obligation arises from justice—every person has a right to their good name until proven otherwise—and from charity, which demands that we treat others as we would wish to be treated. Rash judgment can be venial or mortal depending on the gravity of the fault attributed and the firmness of the false conviction.",
