    category: "morality",
    tags: ["sin", "speech", "eighth-commandment", "reputation"],
    oneLiner: "Two distinct sins against a neighbor's reputation: detraction reveals true faults without just cause, while calumny attributes false ones.",
    body: "Detraction and calumny are both sins against the eighth commandment, but they differ in kind. Detraction consists in disclosing the real faults or failings of another person to someone who has no right or need to know, thereby unjustly diminishing the person's reputation. Calumny (slander) goes further by attributing faults that the person does not actually possess—it is lying about another to harm their reputation. Both sins create an obligation of restitution: the detractor must try to restore the injured reputation, and the calumniator must retract the false statement and repair the damage. St. Thomas teaches that calumny is more grave because it adds the malice of lying to the injustice against reputation.",
