    oneLiner: "The moral obligation to restore what has been unjustly taken or to repair damage caused by one's sinful actions.",
    body: "Restitution is a requirement of commutative justice that obliges anyone who has unjustly taken or damaged another's property, reputation, or rights to make amends as far as possible. St. Augustine's famous axiom—'The sin is not forgiven unless what was stolen is restored'—does not mean forgiveness is impossible without restitution, but that genuine repentance necessarily includes the will to repair harm done. Restitution applies to material theft, damage to reputation (through detraction or calumny), violation of contracts, and other forms of injustice. When direct restitution is impossible (e.g., the victim is unknown or deceased), the obligation may be fulfilled through charity to the poor or other means determined by a confessor.",
