    oneLiner: "Two opposite sins against the theological virtue of hope: presumption expects salvation without merit or repentance, while despair denies God's willingness to save.",
    body: "The theological virtue of hope can be destroyed by excess (presumption) or deficiency (despair). Presumption takes two forms: presuming on one's own abilities to achieve salvation without God's grace, or presuming on God's mercy to forgive without repentance or effort to amend one's life. Despair is the abandonment of hope in God's mercy—the conviction that one's sins are too great for God to forgive or that salvation is impossible. Both sins are grave because they strike at the fundamental relationship between God and the soul. The Catechism (CCC 2091-2092) treats them as sins against the first commandment. Judas's sin was not betrayal alone but the despair that followed it, while the presumptuous sinner uses God's mercy as a license to keep sinning.",
    example: "A man reasons that since God is merciful, he can continue living in serious sin and simply confess on his deathbed—this is presumption. Conversely, a woman who has had an abortion and believes God could never forgive her falls into despair.",
    whyItMatters: "Understanding these two extremes helps Catholics navigate the narrow path of authentic hope: trusting in God's mercy while taking seriously the demands of conversion. Both presumption and despair are traps that distort the true face of God.",
    relatedTerms: ["spx-sins-against-faith", "spx-scandal-theological", "spx-restitution-justice"]
