    body: "Simony takes its name from Simon Magus (Acts 8:9-24), who offered the apostles money in exchange for the power to confer the Holy Spirit. It encompasses any attempt to buy or sell spiritual things—sacraments, indulgences, ecclesiastical offices, blessings, or relics—or to attach a temporal price to what is freely given by God. The sin can be committed by giving money (munus a manu), flattery or service (munus a lingua), or influence (munus ab obsequio) in exchange for spiritual goods. Canon law excommunicates those who commit simony in connection with the sacraments (CIC 1380). The medieval Church fought simony extensively, as it corrupted the appointment of bishops and pastors.",
