    category: "morality",
    tags: ["sin", "sacred", "profanation", "gravity"],
    oneLiner: "The profanation or unworthy treatment of sacred persons, places, or things, classified into personal, local, and real sacrilege.",
    body: "Sacrilege is the violation or contemptuous treatment of what is consecrated to God. Moral theology distinguishes three types. Personal sacrilege is committed against persons consecrated to God (e.g., violence against a priest or religious, or sins of impurity committed by those under religious vows). Local sacrilege profanes sacred places (e.g., committing a crime in a church, using a church for secular purposes without permission). Real sacrilege is the profanation of sacred objects or sacraments (e.g., receiving the Eucharist in a state of mortal sin, desecrating sacred vessels, or selling consecrated hosts). The gravity of sacrilege depends on the dignity of what is profaned; thus sacrilege against the Eucharist is the most serious.",
