    oneLiner: "The sinful practice of charging excessive interest on loans, condemned by the Church as a violation of justice toward the borrower.",
    body: "Catholic teaching on usury has developed significantly over the centuries. The early Church, following the Old Testament prohibition (Deut 23:19) and Aristotle's critique of money breeding money, condemned all interest on loans (mutuum) as intrinsically unjust. Medieval councils reinforced this prohibition. As the economy became more complex, moral theologians distinguished between a loan of consumption (where charging interest remains unjust) and legitimate titles to compensation—such as lucrum cessans (profit foregone) and damnum emergens (loss incurred). Modern Catholic social teaching focuses on the underlying principle: exploiting a borrower's need to extract unjust profit is sinful, while reasonable interest reflecting genuine costs and risks may be legitimate.",
    example: "A payday lending company charges a 400% annual interest rate to borrowers in desperate circumstances. Catholic moral theology would identify this as usury because the lender exploits the borrower's vulnerability for disproportionate gain.",
