    tags: ["social-doctrine", "governance", "family", "common-good"],
    oneLiner: "The principle that decisions should be made at the lowest competent level of society, with higher authorities intervening only when lower ones cannot act effectively.",
    body: "Subsidiarity, articulated by Pope Pius XI in Quadragesimo Anno (1931), holds that 'it is an injustice and at the same time a grave evil and disturbance of right order to assign to a greater and higher association what lesser and subordinate organizations can do.' This means that families, parishes, local communities, and voluntary associations should handle what they can, with the state stepping in only when these smaller bodies are genuinely unable to meet a need. Subsidiarity works in tandem with solidarity: while solidarity demands that the strong help the weak, subsidiarity ensures that this help empowers rather than replaces local initiative. The principle applies to Church governance as well, supporting the role of diocesan bishops and local pastors.",
