    body: "The preferential option for the poor was formally articulated at the Latin American bishops' conferences at Medellin (1968) and Puebla (1979), though its roots lie deep in Scripture and Tradition. Jesus identified Himself with the hungry, thirsty, naked, and imprisoned (Matt 25:31-46). The Church Fathers taught that the poor have a special claim on the community's resources. Pope John Paul II clarified that the option is 'preferential' but not exclusive—it does not mean neglecting other groups but ensuring that the poor are not forgotten. It applies to personal charity, institutional structures, and public policy. The option is theological before it is political: God Himself shows a special love for those the world discards.",
