    category: "scripture",
    tags: ["covenant", "salvation-history", "typology", "unity"],
    oneLiner: "The theological framework that reads the Bible as a unified narrative of successive covenants through which God progressively reveals His plan of salvation.",
    body: "Covenant theology interprets Scripture through the lens of the major covenants God established with humanity: the Adamic, Noahic, Abrahamic, Mosaic, Davidic, and New Covenants. Each covenant builds upon the previous ones, progressively revealing God's plan to form a people for Himself and ultimately redeem all creation through Christ. Unlike dispensationalism, which emphasizes sharp discontinuities between biblical eras, Catholic covenant theology stresses organic development and fulfillment. The New Covenant does not abolish but fulfills all prior covenants. This framework, developed by scholars like Scott Hahn, provides a powerful tool for understanding how the Old and New Testaments form a single coherent story.",
    example: "A Bible study group traces how God's promise to Abraham that 'all nations will be blessed through you' (Gen 12:3) is progressively fulfilled through David's kingdom and ultimately realized when Christ commissions the apostles to make disciples of 'all nations' (Matt 28:19).",
