    id: "spx-mosaic-covenant-law",
    term: "Mosaic Covenant and Law",
    category: "scripture",
    tags: ["covenant", "law", "sinai", "torah"],
    oneLiner: "The conditional covenant at Sinai in which Israel received the Torah as the terms of its relationship with God, serving as a pedagogue leading to Christ.",
    body: "The Mosaic covenant, established at Sinai (Exodus 19-24), is unique among the biblical covenants in being explicitly conditional: 'If you obey my voice and keep my covenant, you shall be my treasured possession' (Ex 19:5). The 613 commandments of the Torah governed Israel's worship (ceremonial law), civil life (judicial law), and moral conduct (moral law). Catholic theology, following St. Thomas Aquinas, teaches that the ceremonial and judicial laws were fulfilled and superseded by the New Covenant, while the moral law (summarized in the Ten Commandments) remains permanently binding. Paul describes the Law as a 'pedagogue' (Gal 3:24) that prepared Israel for Christ by revealing sin and humanity's need for grace.",
    example: "When Jesus says 'I have come not to abolish the Law but to fulfill it' (Matt 5:17), He affirms the permanent validity of the moral law while indicating that the ceremonial laws (dietary restrictions, animal sacrifices) find their completion in His own sacrifice.",
    whyItMatters: "The Mosaic covenant is essential for understanding why Christ came and what He accomplished. Without grasping the Law's role as pedagogue, Christians cannot fully appreciate the freedom and grace that the New Covenant brings.",
