    term: "Wisdom Literature Overview",
    category: "scripture",
    tags: ["old-testament", "wisdom", "proverbs", "sirach"],
    oneLiner: "The biblical books—Proverbs, Job, Ecclesiastes, Wisdom, Sirach, Song of Songs, and certain Psalms—that explore the art of living well in God's created order.",
    body: "The wisdom literature of the Bible addresses the practical and philosophical dimensions of life under God's sovereignty. Proverbs teaches practical wisdom through short maxims. Job confronts innocent suffering. Ecclesiastes (Qoheleth) wrestles with the apparent futility of human endeavor. The Wisdom of Solomon (deuterocanonical) personifies Wisdom as a divine attribute. Sirach (Ecclesiasticus) offers extended moral instruction. The Song of Songs celebrates love—human and divine. Catholic interpretation reads these books both literally and spiritually: Wisdom personified is understood as a foreshadowing of Christ (1 Cor 1:24), and the Song of Songs is read as an allegory of God's love for Israel and Christ's love for the Church.",
