    category: "scripture",
    tags: ["genre", "revelation", "daniel", "eschatology"],
    oneLiner: "A biblical literary genre using symbolic visions, cosmic imagery, and dualistic conflict to reveal God's hidden plan for the triumph of good over evil.",
    body: "Apocalyptic literature (from the Greek apokalypsis, 'unveiling') is found in Daniel, portions of Ezekiel, Isaiah 24-27, Zechariah 9-14, and the Book of Revelation. Its characteristics include symbolic numbers (7, 12, 666), cosmic imagery (beasts, thrones, heavenly courts), heavenly journeys, and a sharp dualism between good and evil. This genre emerged in times of persecution and crisis to assure the faithful that God remains sovereign despite appearances. Catholic interpretation avoids both fundamentalist literalism (reading every symbol as a one-to-one prediction) and dismissive skepticism (treating the texts as merely human imagination). The Pontifical Biblical Commission encourages reading apocalyptic texts within the larger context of Catholic theology and tradition.",
