    oneLiner: "The distinctive theological vision of John's Gospel, Letters, and Revelation, centered on the incarnate Logos, divine love, and the realized presence of eternal life.",
    body: "Johannine theology is characterized by several distinctive themes: the Logos (Word) who was with God and was God, becoming flesh to dwell among us (John 1:1-14); a high Christology in which Jesus's divine identity is revealed through seven 'I AM' statements; the centrality of love (agape) as the defining mark of discipleship; a 'realized eschatology' in which eternal life begins now through faith rather than only at the end of time; and the role of the Holy Spirit as Paraclete (Advocate) who guides the Church into all truth. John's Gospel is the most theologically developed of the four, and the early Church called John 'the Theologian' for this reason. His writings profoundly shaped the development of Trinitarian and Christological doctrine.",
