    id: "spx-pauline-theology-overview",
    term: "Pauline Theology Overview",
    category: "scripture",
    tags: ["paul", "justification", "grace", "body-of-christ"],
    oneLiner: "The comprehensive theological vision of St. Paul's letters, centered on justification by grace through faith, the Body of Christ, and the universal scope of salvation.",
    body: "Paul's thirteen epistles articulate a theology that profoundly shaped Christian doctrine. Key themes include: justification—being made righteous before God not by works of the Law but by grace through faith in Christ (Rom 3:28; Gal 2:16); the Church as the Body of Christ in which all members share organic unity (1 Cor 12); the contrast between flesh and spirit as orientations of the whole person toward or away from God; the cosmic significance of Christ's death and resurrection; and the universality of salvation extended to Gentiles as well as Jews. Catholic interpretation of Paul, especially since the Council of Trent and the Joint Declaration on Justification (1999), emphasizes that faith and works are not opposed but cooperate under grace.",
    example: "When Paul writes 'It is no longer I who live, but Christ who lives in me' (Gal 2:20), he expresses the transformative reality of baptismal incorporation into Christ that Catholic theology calls sanctifying grace.",
