    tags: ["jesus-prayer", "russian", "hesychasm", "prayer"],
    oneLiner: "A nineteenth-century Russian spiritual classic recounting a pilgrim's journey to learn unceasing prayer through the Jesus Prayer, valued in Catholic contemplative tradition.",
    body: "The Way of a Pilgrim is an anonymous nineteenth-century Russian text that narrates the journey of a simple peasant who seeks to fulfill St. Paul's command to 'pray without ceasing' (1 Thess 5:17). A staretz (elder) teaches him the Jesus Prayer and instructs him to repeat it thousands of times daily until it descends from the lips into the heart and begins to pray itself. The pilgrim's journey across Russia becomes an allegory for the interior journey toward God. Though Orthodox in origin, the book has been embraced by Catholic contemplatives and recommended by spiritual directors as a practical introduction to repetitive prayer and the prayer of the heart. It complements the Western tradition of the rosary and aspiratory prayer.",
    example: "A Catholic retreat director recommends The Way of a Pilgrim to a retreatant who struggles with discursive meditation, and the retreatant discovers that the simplicity of the Jesus Prayer opens a door to contemplative prayer that more complex methods had kept closed.",
    whyItMatters: "This text demonstrates the deep kinship between Eastern and Western Christian spirituality. It shows that the aspiration to unceasing prayer is not an unrealistic ideal but an achievable practice, and it enriches Catholic prayer life with the riches of the Eastern tradition.",
