    id: "spx-interior-castle-structure",
    term: "Interior Castle Structure",
    category: "mysticism",
    tags: ["teresa-of-avila", "mansions", "prayer", "stages"],
    oneLiner: "St. Teresa of Avila's masterwork mapping the soul's journey to God through seven successive 'mansions' or dwelling places within the interior castle of the soul.",
    body: "Written in 1577, The Interior Castle describes the soul as a crystal castle with seven concentric sets of rooms (moradas/mansions). The first three mansions correspond to the purgative way: the soul moves from habitual sin through the practice of virtue and regular prayer. The fourth mansion marks the transition from active to passive prayer, where God begins to act more directly. The fifth mansion involves the prayer of union, which Teresa compares to the silkworm entering its cocoon. The sixth mansion is the most turbulent, marked by spiritual trials, ecstasies, and the deepening of love. The seventh mansion is spiritual marriage—a permanent, peaceful union with God at the center of the soul. Teresa insists that progress through the mansions is not linear and that humility and self-knowledge accompany every stage.",
    example: "A spiritual director uses the Interior Castle to help a directee understand that her recent experience of spiritual dryness and painful purification is actually a sign of progress—she is being drawn from the third mansion into the fourth, where God takes the initiative.",
    whyItMatters: "The Interior Castle remains the most systematic and psychologically realistic map of the contemplative journey in Catholic tradition. It normalizes the difficulties of spiritual growth and gives hope that the struggles have a purpose and a destination.",
