    body: "Franciscan spirituality flows from St. Francis's radical conversion experience, in which he heard Christ say from the crucifix of San Damiano: 'Rebuild my church.' Its distinctive marks are: evangelical poverty as a participation in Christ's own self-emptying (Phil 2:5-8); reverence for creation as a window to the Creator (expressed in the Canticle of the Sun); devotion to the Incarnation and Passion of Christ (Francis created the first Christmas creche and received the stigmata); minority and humility (the friars are called 'Friars Minor'); and joyful simplicity. The Franciscan intellectual tradition, represented by St. Bonaventure and Blessed John Duns Scotus, emphasizes the primacy of love and the will, complementing the Dominican emphasis on intellect. Franciscan missionaries carried the Gospel to the New World, China, and the Holy Land.",
