    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["benedict", "ora-et-labora", "stability", "rule"],
    oneLiner: "The spirituality of St. Benedict's Rule, structured around the balance of prayer and work (ora et labora), stability of place, and the search for God in community.",
    body: "Benedictine spirituality is shaped by the Rule of St. Benedict (c. 530), one of the most influential documents in Western civilization. Its core principles are: the opus Dei (work of God)—the Liturgy of the Hours as the monk's primary duty; lectio divina as daily spiritual nourishment; manual labor as sanctifying and humbling; stability (commitment to one community and place); conversatio morum (ongoing conversion of life); and obedience to the abbot as a representative of Christ. The Rule's opening word, 'Listen' (Obsculta), establishes attentiveness as the fundamental Benedictine virtue. Benedict's balance of prayer, work, study, and rest created a sustainable pattern of life that preserved Western learning through the Dark Ages and continues to attract laypeople seeking rhythm and order in their spiritual lives.",
