    body: "Jesuit (Ignatian) spirituality springs from the Spiritual Exercises of St. Ignatius of Loyola (1491-1556), a four-week retreat program designed to help retreatants discern God's will through the use of imagination, affective prayer, and the discernment of spirits. Key principles include: finding God in all things (not only in prayer but in work, relationships, and the world); the magis (always seeking the greater glory of God); indifference (spiritual freedom from disordered attachments); the daily Examen; and contemplation in action (being a contemplative even amid active ministry). The Society of Jesus applies this spirituality to education, missionary work, scholarly research, social justice, and pastoral ministry. Ignatian spirituality is unique in its adaptability—it was designed for active apostles in the world, not cloistered monks.",
