    term: "Moral Argument for God (Deeper)",
    category: "apologetics",
    tags: ["natural-theology", "ethics", "objective-morality", "lewis"],
    oneLiner: "The argument that the existence of objective moral truths requires a transcendent moral lawgiver, pointing to God as the foundation of the moral order.",
    body: "The Moral Argument proceeds: (1) If objective moral values and duties exist, then God exists as their ground and source. (2) Objective moral values and duties do exist (as evidenced by universal moral intuitions such as the wrongness of torturing innocents for pleasure). (3) Therefore, God exists. The argument does not claim that atheists cannot be moral but that without God, morality lacks an objective foundation and reduces to subjective preference or social convention. C.S. Lewis popularized this argument in Mere Christianity, and it has been developed philosophically by Robert Adams, William Lane Craig, and others. Catholic natural law theory, following Aquinas, holds that moral law is grounded in God's eternal law and knowable by reason.",
    example: "When confronted with a moral atrocity like the Holocaust, virtually everyone recognizes it as objectively wrong—not merely culturally unpopular. The Moral Argument asks: what grounds this universal judgment if not a transcendent standard of goodness?",
    whyItMatters: "In a relativistic culture, the Moral Argument challenges the claim that morality is merely subjective. It shows that the moral convictions people cannot abandon actually point beyond themselves to a moral lawgiver who is the standard of goodness.",
    relatedTerms: ["spx-argument-from-desire-deeper", "spx-kalam-argument", "spx-consciousness-argument"]
